answers.body_markdown:
It is a good idea to keep the constructor simple.  In your case it is complicated by interacting with another object.  One reason is error handling which can be difficult in constructors.

Instead of using a constructor with a parameter, remove the parameter and call it like this.

    var newBody = new Body();
    newBody.setParent(parent);

The constructor would look like this.

    public Body() {
        this.children = new TreeSet&lt;Body&gt;;
    }

And change the setParent method to check for no current parent.

    public synchronized void setParent(Body newParent) {
        if (parent != null)
            parent.removeChild(this);
        parent = newParent;
        if (newParent != null)
            newParent.addChild(this);
    }

Notice that I also changed the name of the setParent parameter to not collide with the class variable.  Hard to find errors occur when you forget to use &quot;this&quot; in order to distinguish which &quot;parent&quot; you are referring to.

The constructor code I removed was really just a duplication of the setParent method anyway.

I added synchronized to the method so that you are assured that multiple calls to this method are done synchronously, otherwise the hierarchy could get damaged.

Of course, there are many ways to accomplish this.  But this is a simple way that I would use.

